<TEXT>
storms soaked eastern texas louisiana and georgia on monday 
lightning blacked out a colorado mountain city and temperatures 
soared in michigan and south dakota 
rain showers and occasional thunderstorms reached from western 
south carolina and georgia across eastern texas and southeast 
oklahoma showers and thunderstorms also developed in the dakotas 
southern montana northern wyoming and northwest colorado as well 
as northwest new mexico 
lightning strikes caused a power outage affecting much of craig 
colo 
in monroe la 375 inches of rain fell between 5 and 7 pm 
the hard dry ground didnt absorb the water which rose fast and 
flooded streets several central louisiana towns got an inch or 
more of rain monday night 
thunderstorms produced 2 inches of rain between north houston 
and humble texas and about 1 inches in western and northwest 
harris county texas 
other heavier rainfall during the 6 hours ending at 2 pm edt 
included 1 inches at macon ga and almost onehalf inch at 
mcallen and longview texas 
at least three michigan cities reached high temperature records 
for july 4 by early afternoon with a recordtying 88 degrees in 
alpena and recordbreaking 92 in flint and 90 in marquette 
south dakota also sweltered through the holiday with rapid city 
and aberdeen setting records for the date with 105 degrees 
temperatures around the nation at 3 pm edt ranged from 56 
degrees at san simeon calif to 102 degrees at yuma ariz the 
nations low monday morning was 38 degrees at truckee calif 
the national weather forecast for tuesday called for showers and 
thunderstorms from florida across alabama southern mississippi and 
louisiana and from northern montana across the northern pacific 
coast 
high temperatures should be in the upper 80s and the 90s over 
the appalachians the great lakes the eastern gulf much of the 
ohio tennessee mississippi and missouri valleys the plains the 
lower rockies nevada and the southern plateau highs in the 60s 
and 70s were forecast along much of the pacific coast temperatures 
in the southwests deserts could reach 115 degrees high 
temperatures over the rest of the nation were generally predicted 
to reach the 80s 
