<TEXT>
rose phillipine duchesne a frenchborn nun 
who worked among american indians and founded the us branch of 
the society of the sacred heart has become a saint of the roman 
catholic church 
pope john paul ii called phillipine a great pioneer as he 
canonized her sunday in a solemn ceremony in st peters basilica 
he also proclaimed a spanish member of the trinitarian order 
the rev simon de rojas among those catholics who through their 
life and works are officially recognized by the church as being in 
heaven and worthy of honor 
born into a prominent french family in 1769 philippine was in 
her 30s when she joined the order of the society of the sacred 
heart founded by st madeleine sophie barat in 1800 to educate 
young women 
she became the societys first missionary in 1818 she and four 
other nuns traveled to missouri where they founded several 
schools including what the society says was the first free school 
for the poor in the united states 
from the midwest the order spread to the east and west coast 
and later to canada cuba mexico and new zealand 
the society now has 5500 members who are involved in education 
spiritual guidance and pastoral work in 40 countries including 
japan uganda india and korea and throughout europe north 
america and south america 
in his homily during the canonization mass john paul speaking 
in english praised philippines missionary courage and held her up 
as a reminder that the call to holiness is universal and does not 
know the boundaries of nation political system culture or race 
when she was 72 philippine fulfilled her dream to work with the 
indians when she founded the sugar creek mission among the 
potawatomi tribe in kansas 
after only a year illness and old age forced her back to the 
convent in st charles mo where she died in 1852 but in the 
short time she spent with them the indians were so impressed by 
the time she spent on her knees that they called her 
quahkahkanum the woman who always prays 
more than 7ooo nuns alumnae and students of the society of the 
sacred heart were at sundays ceremony concelebrated by eight 
bishops and cardinals including the archbishop of st louis john 
l may among them was a family of potowatomi indians headed by 
gerald tuckwin who is dean of liberal arts at haskell indian 
junior college in lawrence kan 
since the second vatican council the society while maintaining 
its dedication to the education of young women has devoted much of 
its energy to work among the underprivileged 
speaking to the 20000 pilgrims gathered in the basilica for the 
canonization the pope recalled philippine duchesnes radical 
commitment to the poor and said it should be a living 
inspiration to the society and to all religious of today 
de rojas born in 1552 devoted his life to work among the poor 
and to promoting devotion to the virgin mary as well as being 
confessor to the spanish royal family he died in 1624 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

