<DOCNO> AP880704-0019 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
a growing blight threatens to destroy the 
nations entire hazelnut crop and experts here are trying to find 
a way to control the plant disease 
all of the united states 20000ton hazelnut harvest comes from 
oregons willamette valley where favorable conditions enable 
farmers to turn out hazelnuts or filberts prized worldwide for 
their size and high quality 
but eastern filbert blight once confined to the eastern united 
states has taken hold here since its discovery in washington in 
1970 and is spreading in an everwidening arch in the northern 
willamette valley 
the united states produces just 3 percent of the worlds 
hazelnut crop experts say the nations share could grow if they 
can develop a variety that shares the qualities of the current 
filbert strains and is immune to the blight 
the worlds other major hazelnut producers are turkey italy and 
spain where the blight is unknown 
eastern filbert blight is endemic to north americas native 
eastern hazelnut and because it also attacks european varieties 
farmers have been unable to successfully grow hazelnuts east of the 
rocky mountains 
however the european varieties prospered in the pacific 
northwest where the native western hazelnut is immune to the 
blight until the disease took hold among the european stock 
the european varieties are preferred because they have desirable 
commercial qualities lacking in the western variety which grows 
wild along fence rows and is known as hazel brush 
scientists are working to control the blights spread until a 
breeding program at oregon state university produces a strain 
immune to the disease an accomplishment believed to be years away 
we need a way to slow down the spread of the disease so we 
still have an industry when the resistant strains become 
available said shawn mehlenbacher an assistant professor at 
oregon state and director of the breeding program 
the disease spreads when spores that develop on infected wood 
are washed by the rain or blown by the wind to other plants 
hazelnuts in the wild grow like a bush but growers prune the 
bushes to make them grow from a single stem like a tree to check 
the spread of the blight further pruning is used to remove 
diseased parts of the trees infected wood is then burned 
growers also use a copperbased fungicide that kills spores 
to find a permanent solution researchers have begun seeking an 
alternative to the daviana variety of hazelnut which is used as a 
pollinizer 
in a typical orchard 89 percent of the plants will be of a 
variety such as barcelona and 11 percent daviana mehlenbacher 
said the daviana plants pollinate the barcelona variety which 
cannot pollinate itself 
but daviana appears to be particularly susceptible to the 
blight mehlenbacher said 
as an alternative research has focused on a variety known as 
gasaway which is immune to the blight but has drawbacks such as 
poor kernel quality and a small nut 
distribution of offspring of four blightresistant seedlings 
bred from the gasaway variety will begin in january mehlenbacher 
said nurseries will graft these plants onto rootstock to produce 
new plants that will be immune to the blight mehlenbacher said 
the breeding program eventually will offer a replacement for the 
barcelona variety probably a plant descended from the gasaway 
type but that will take about 18 years 
additional sources of resistance are being sought in hybrids of 
the western and european varieties but those will take 25 years or 
more to develop mehlenbacher said 
growers are confident alternatives will be found to protect the 
industry said jay nelson chairman of oregons filbert commission 
well conquer it nelson said itll just take us time 
</TEXT>
