<TEXT>
the man who trained dolphins for the television 
series flipper and tamed orca the killer whale is going to 
china to help save the rare chinese river dolphin from extinction 
the freshwater dolphins called baiji once flourished in 
chinas rivers and lakes but pollution and river traffic have 
reduced their numbers 
fewer than 300 are left in the yangtze river 
ric obarry 48 is leaving this month for a monthlong 
factfinding trip he says getting the chinese government to 
understand what it will take to save the baiji from extinction may 
be half the battle 
the chinese plan to build a seminatural preserve by closing off 
a loop of the river then obarry hopes to capture as many of the 
dolphins as possible and move them to the preserve 
they have to be taken to this place settle down fall in love 
and start making babies obarry said were talking about 
repopulating the species and that could take many years 
obarry said moving the dolphins could be as dangerous as 
leaving them in the river unless its done right 
keeping dolphins calm during jolting moves in trucks or 
helicopters is vital because they dont breathe automatically 
obarry said any time they want to end their life they simply 
dont take the next breath 
since marine mammal husbandry is practically an unknown field in 
china obarry also hopes to communicate his love for the playful 
dolphins to the chinese 
they need to be as careful as they can and build a beautiful 
spot for them to survive he said its the same problem they 
had with the panda until they got worldwide exposure no one knew 
about the problem 
obarry is borrowing 3000 from his sons college fund to make 
the trip and is looking for a corporate sponsor for the baiji 
project 
the chinese government is not putting much money into this 
obarry said not that they dont care theyre just overwhelmed 
by human problems 
chinese scientists have been studying several wounded baiji they 
nursed back to health in a tank but capturing and moving an entire 
population was beyond their expertise and their budget obarry 
said dr xhou kaiya dean of nanjing normal university contacted 
him in hopes of leading a worldwide effort to save the species 
as a trainer at miamis seaquarium in the 1960s obarry taught 
five dolphins to play the part of flipper on tv but to hear 
obarry tell it the dolphins were the ones training him 
dolphins are far more intelligent in our world than we are in 
theirs obarry said its taken about 25 years but i can see 
things from their point of view 
through the dolphin project obarry has spent years lobbying 
marine animal shows and other organizations to release captive 
dolphins into the wild he admits that his solution to the baijis 
predicament isolating them in a manmade preserve is sadly 
ironic 
its like the pandas he said the only ones to survive 
will be born in captivity its either that or let them become 
extinct 
