<TEXT>
the ruling institutional revolutionary party 
which has dominated mexican politics for almost 60 years faces a 
tough test wednesday in which its credibility is at stake 
few doubt that the the pri will win in the july 6 presidential 
elections 
the question is whether this party which has monopolized past 
contests will emerge with a landslide victory or clinch barely 
enough votes to continue its mandate 
the pri has defied political logic by never losing a 
presidential election or gubernatorial race in any of mexicos 31 
states since it was founded in 1929 but it also has been accused 
of stuffing ballot boxes to give itself almost incredible 
victories with anywhere from 74 to 95 percent of the vote 
this time party officials privately admit that they would be 
satisfied with 50 percent of the vote 
the pri is under pressure both from its members and the 
opposition to change the system that has kept many poor mexicans 
politically passive although it has pushed the economy to grow 
but many mexicans were angered by the economic crises of the 
1970s and early 1980s which they believe were brought on by the 
partys inept administration reckless borrowing and brazen 
corruption 
as a result president miguel de la madrid has spent his six 
years in office trying to control inflation and a foreign debt now 
exceeding 100 billion and to push up the mexican peso whose 
value dropped from 23 to the dollar in 1980 to 2300 to the dollar 
this week 
de la madrid has managed to pull inflation down to 36 percent 
for the first five months of this year compared to a record 159 
percent in 1987 
neverthless his party is virtually under political siege 
the erosion discredit and lack of credibility of the 
political system is such that even if it wins the elections its 
capacity to govern will depend on how it wins wrote political 
analyst jorge castaneda 
carlos salinas de gortari a certain winner as the presidential 
candidate of the pri is a harvardeducated economist who sounds 
like a reformist pointing out the vices of the system once 
elected de gortaris term will last until 1994 
 
in his campaign de gortari speaks of the need to democratize a 
