speakers on partisan or ideological grounds but capitol hill 
overseers say the programs problems appear to have been dealt with 
adequately 
we dont have any complaints that are pending now said rep 
dan mica dfla chairman of the house foreign affairs 
subcommittee on international operations i think its a 
tremendous program but it was abused for a while weve 
straightened that out 
joseph oconnell an official at usias public liaison office 
said the agency tries to take a politically balanced approach to 
selecting speakers for the program 
he said that for obvious reasons we dont want to make it look 
like were leaning toward vice president george bush who is 
all but certain to be the republican nominee running against 
democrat michael dukakis in the fall presidential race 
in some cases usias approach this election year has led to 
sending of democratrepublican teams to appear sidebyside before 
foreign audiences 
for example political consultant ed rollins manager of 
president reagans 1984 reelection campaign this month traveled 
to west germany with les francis another consultant who served as 
deputy chief of staff in the carter white house 
francis said that during the weeklong trip they spoke to 
political professionals academics students journalists and 
business people in four cities bonn hamburg nuremberg and 
mannheim 
he found german audiences already well versed in the basics of 
american politics but eager to learn more about the nuances of this 
years campaign 
they can read about what dukakis might think about the mx or 
the midgetman mobile missile or they can read about what george 
bushs resume is in terms of foreign policy experience 
but to get a feel for how these guys conduct their campaigns 
the kind of people around them thats ultimately as important to 
the presidency as position papers or biographical sketches and i 
think thats what they were interested in as much as anything 
francis said 
another speaking team involved thomas susman a washington 
attorney active in democratic politics and loren smith a 
conservative republican who served as counsel to reagans 1980 
campaign and is now chief judge of the us claims courts they 
spent three weeks in march visiting the philippines pakistan 
turkey and egypt 
susman noted that we went to countries where the party which 
is out of power doesnt want to just win the next election they 
want to kill the people in power they want a new constitution 
they want new forms of government 
and so the example of people from the united states who have 
opposing perspectives but who talk rationally about issues and 
personalities with each other was something that we were told was 
quite impressive he said 
other speakers include 
benjamin ginsburg director of cornell universitys institute 
for public affairs who traveled to west germany norway spain and 
portugal 
you always understand your own politics better from afar 
ginsburg said americans are very ethnocentric we see the 
universe revolving around the united states and its very useful 
to step outside the united states and see the us through somebody 
elses eyes it freshens your own perspective 
jerry hagstrom author of a recently published book beyond 
reagan the new landscape of american politics and a 
contributing editor of the national journal a washingtonbased 
weekly he visited finland switzerland and china 
hagstrom said his chinese audiences included young scholars 
who had just returned from spending five years in the united 
states but within the same audience you would have young 
graduate students who have never left china with them you had to 
explain what is a caucus and what is a primary 
james lengle a professor of government at georgetown 
university who lectured gave press interviews and made other 
appearances in australia and fiji on fiji he said everyone was 
very much confused about how the parties go about picking their 
nominees and how actually the president is elected 
samuel shipley chairman of the delaware democratic committee 
who traveled to denmark italy and iceland shipley said he was 
impressed at how much less it costs candidates to run for office in 
those countries by comparison with the united states where money 
has become the cancer of politics 
in may 1984 usia director charles z wick appeared before 
micas international operations subcommittee as it investigated the 
blacklisting charges 
